SIMPLE: caption
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Caption
<hw>Cap"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>captio</ets>, fr. <ets>caper</ets> to take. In senses 3 and 4,
perhaps confounded in meaning with L. <ets>caput</ets> a head. See
<er>Capacious</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A caviling; a sophism.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This doctrine is for <qex>caption</qex> and contradiction.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of taking or arresting a person by judicial
process.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Bouvier.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>That part of a legal instrument, as
a commission, indictment, etc., which shows where, when, and by what
authority, it was taken, found, or executed.</def> <rj><au>Bouvier.</au>
<au>Wharton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The heading of a chapter, section, or page.</def>
<mark>[U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Captious</ent>⟦br⟧
